. Yes, you can fake a mime type. The secure way to test image types is not by extension or mime types but actually try to get image data only a true image mime type would offer. Most PHP developers have relied on using getimagesize() to best detect a valid image.
Alternately if you have the ability save all uploads in a folder with a .htaccess file restricting any kind of CGI executing you can make it even more difficult for hackers.
RemoveHandler .cgi .shtm .shtml
RemoveType .php .php3 .php4 .php5
<FilesMatch "\.(cgi|p[ly]|php[345]?|[sp]html?)$">
deny from all
</FilesMatch>
Options -ExecCGI -Includes
Also, simply opening an image via URL or using an img tag is not enough to execute PHP from an image. They would have to execute it from a PHP script or parser or set the image extension as a PHP mime type. So always display images using the img tag and never as an include or similar method.
. Additionally, sanitize all data you may pull from an image file if you must use PHP. There is a way to hide PHP in other parts of the image such as the EXIF headers. But again, must be executed via PHP. Typically this exploit requires special arrangement of commands to pull off and you won't see it's use in the wild aside from shared script snippets, WP templates, etc. But it is still a possibility in some setups. - http://blog.sucuri.net/2013/07/malware-hidden-inside-jpg-exif-headers.html
. If you haven't done it yet enable the extension renaming fix by @noosalife in issue #169 just in case. I found that even if you prevent the PHP mime-type uploads and have restricted access rules for the extension you can fake the mime, upload as a png, and just rename the extension once uploaded. The access rules will lock and hide the PHP file within elFinder but it will sit on the server ready for execution as long as the hacker knows the URL.
I also found I can bypass the upload restrictions by net mounting a drive, copying a PHP file from my server to the victims. And it completely ignores the upload permissions. The file access rules apply, but again I can execute it as long as I know the URL. My .htaccess snippet above can help prevent it's execution from direct access but I am going to work on a fix when I have a chance this weekend. Even though elFinder is not in charge of preventing PHP attacks I would think it not checking the upload mime-types via copy from another server qualifies that as broken and merits a fix.
