StephenNeate:
Whilst this may not be the most elegant solution to the rename issue it is one way to solve it...
If you update the file elFinderVolumeDriver.class.php and insert the below inside the top of function "rename" line 1240 it will check against the original file name, use that extension so that even if someone renames the file to a new extension only the original is used.  (it will work if the file name has multiple periods in the name, and if the user wipes out the extension when they rename)
```
    // find extension from original file name by period
    $extension = explode('.',$this->decode($hash));
    // last value is the etension
    $extension = array_pop($extension);
// this is only needed if the file name is not submitted
$newName = $name; 
// find extension from submitted value and remove it from string
$name = explode('.',$name); 
// remove last value (being the extension)
array_pop($name);

// put the newname back together if the extension exists when submitted
if( count($name)>0){
    $name = implode(".", $name).'.'.$extension;
}else{
    // if no extension existed in rename return name with the original extension
    $name = $newName.'.'.$extension;
}

```
I hope this helps anybody else out looking to solve the rename security issue.  
The reason I call this a security issue is that someone could very easily upload a .txt or .jpg file which is actually a PHP file.  Then rename the file through the interface and gain additional access to the domain / server which most likely is not the desired effect for the standard usage of this great little file manager.
. I agree that securing .php files is not a task for elFinder (and security is a large topic all by itself), but it never hurts to have some basic protection to stop users hurting themselves by accident.  Although just ensuring that files can't accidentally or intentionally be renamed to change their file type does not by itself guarantee security, although it cant hurt :)
